n in 1583, Spaniards such as Fadrique Furió Ceriol and Balthazar Ayala used Machiavelli's new vocabulary and theoretical framework to develop an imperial discourse that would be compatible with a militant understanding of Catholic Christianity. In chapters 3, 4 and 5 he demonstrates in detail how Giovanni Botero, Pedro de Ribadeneyra, and their imitators in the anti-Machiavellian reason-of-state tradition in Spain, attack a straw figure of Machiavelli that they have invented for their own rhetorical and ideological purposes, while they simultaneously incorporate key Machiavellian concepts into their own advice. Keith David Howard is an Assistant Professor of Spanish at Florida State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLiterature, Moderny19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical sciencezSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aPolitical sciencezSpainxHistoryy17th century. 0aPolitical science; Spain; History, 16th century. 0aPolitical science; Spain; History, 17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCatholic Christianity.  aEuropean Political Thought.  aImperial Discourse.  aMachiavelli.  aRhetorical Framework.  aSpanish Prose Treatises.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204310240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782043102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782043102/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles